 will do what is called solarization... in other words it is a discoloration from alteration of the molecular structure. This is a show stopper due to its alteration of transparency and structural properties. Given all of these factors governing solarization present in an NLB I can't see how it would not succumb to this show stopper. All I can think of is to perhaps use an alternative fission fuel to uranium... one ideally with a lower boiling point to relax the thermal constrains... or there may be a limit to which the NLB can be scaled. Again I'm no expert... and I can be wrong... hope I am actually a very cool concept that definitly gives one food for thought. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 991<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 9:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> Mylene wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I ran into one hell of a show stopper. Fused silica and quartz when exposed to high heat... high UV x-ray and gamma flux... and neutron bombardment will do what is called solarization... in other words it is a discoloration from alteration of the molecular structure. This is a show stopper due to its alteration of transparency and structural properties.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Bingo!<br>
